[img[college]]\n[[Go back to the begining|Start]]\n\nreflection: In beginning, my math experience was not a great one, especially in high school. The main reason for this was because, in the beginning, I couldn’t connect the real world with math. I saw numbers and formulas that were only relevant to the textbook. My teachers didn’t help either. I was never given fair and straight answers;a lot of the time i felt insulted. And I believe that is what a teacher should not do. When I become a teacher, I would try to answer all the questions I know and if I don’t know, I will tell the student I will find out and let him/her know later. This way I will learn too. My thinking of math changed in my physics class where math was connected to the real world. Physics helped me because I can see everything that I was learning in day to day bases. My maths mark didn’t improve, but I gained something more important-the ability to think critically. Although my high school math classes were not a plesent experience, I was able to do great in a university. The knowledge that I gained from thinking critically helped me in higher education. And what more, I was offered to do graduate studies based on my math skills. I learned that teachers should always listen to students before turning him/her down. A teacher should also connect what they are teaching to real-world or other subjects.\n\nMost importantly, I believe that everyone should be given a fair and equal chance to succeed and the best way to do that is if students are taught based on what they find motivating. There is no one way to teach and as a teacher, I should know as many ways as possible. Because I was not too smart or well equipped in the beginning but Physics (in my case) motivated me; It can be something entirely different for someone else.\n\n\nThe End
